Self healing databases for predictive risk analytics in safety-critical systems

1. Introduction
resulting analysis (Raviv et al., 2017; Pence et al., 2017). Accurate, complete and consistent databases of heterogeneous structured and unstructured data provide rich sources for risk analyses in safety-critical systems, but the underlying data can suffer from errors, inconsistencies, conflicting and missing information (Wheatley et al., 2017; Huang et al., 2018).
Risk analyses in safety-critical systems provide essential information to managers, decision-makers and regulators managing risk, and deciding on appropriate risk mitigation measures, on infrastructure improvements, or on capital or infrastructure investment choices. These actions and decisions can have significant economic, safety and envi- ronmental impacts (Merrick et al., 2000, 2002; Caruzzo et al., 2018; Kawasaki et al., 2017) in systems such as nuclear power (Kim et al., 2015); offshore oil and gas (Paltrinieri et al., 2019; Adedigba et al., 2018); aerospace (McGregor et al., 2017); as well as surface (Salay et al., 2018; Feth et al., 2018; Chen et al., 2018), rail (Ghofrani et al., 2018) and marine transportation (Baalisampang et al., 2018; Aziz et al., 2019).
Risk analysis approaches have evolved over the years, and current approaches can utilize affordable and highly capable hardware and software; the availability of integrated real-time situational, operational and environmental data; and the power of advanced analytical tech- niques, including machine learning. Risk analyses utilizing multiple heterogeneous structured (text, numbers) and unstructured (images, videos and sound) data sources of accidents, incidents, near misses and unusual events offer promise in terms of the power and depth of the

Automated approaches to addressing vulnerabilities in large-scale heterogeneous data repositories include data cleaning and truth dis- covery (Sun et al., 2018) and self healing systems (Ghosh et al., 2007; Psaier and Dustdar, 2011). Although some self healing and self repairing capabilities leveraging machine learning and predictive analyses have been employed to prevent the spread of erroneous or missing data from one database to another, to improve data sustainability and database maintenance processes, and ostensibly to improve decision making (Agrawal et al., 2006; Ding et al., 2017; Li et al., 2017), as well as to identify anomalies and monitor quality in structured safety-critical data sets (Muharemi et al., 2019), little attention has focused on addressing shortcomings in heterogeneous—structured and unstructured—safety data sets, the focus of this work. Further, little work has been done to apply self healing techniques to address shortcomings in root cause, accident, incident and near miss databases, the core repositories for risk

ABSTRACT
Assuring the quality, consistency and accuracy of safety data repositories is essential in safety-critical systems. In many systems, however, significant effort is required to identify, address, clean and repair data errors and in- consistencies, and to integrate safety data sets and repositories, particularly for risk analyses. Although some self healing and self repairing capabilities leveraging machine learning and predictive analyses have been employed to identify anomalies and monitor quality in structured safety-critical data sets, little attention has been focused on addressing shortcomings in heterogeneous—structured and unstructured—safety data sets, the focus of this work. The text mining and classification analysis employed in this research indicates that machine learning techniques can be employed to improve the accuracy and robustness of large-scale structured and unstructured database repositories, and to improve the effectiveness and efficiency of safety data repository maintenance. Hybrid machine learning approaches, leveraging machine learning, text mining and natural language processing, offer additional promise in future work.
